Done. I ran 10 iterations of hypothesis-driven analysis on the 50,000-patient CRC cohort using OLS regression with main effects, subgroup, and interaction tests. Both required outputs are in the bundle directory:

- `transcript.json` (validates against `transcript_schema.json`): 10 iterations, 38 hypotheses, 38 analyses with signed effects and p-values.
- `analysis_summary.txt`: narrative synthesis.

Key findings: classical prognostic factors (ECOG, stage IV, right-sided primary, low albumin, high LDH/CEA, RAS/BRAF mutation, weight loss) all behaved as expected and were independently significant. However, none of the canonical biomarker–treatment interactions for metastatic CRC were detectable — cetuximab × RAS-WT, cetuximab × left-sided, encorafenib × BRAF V600E, pembrolizumab × MSI-high, and trastuzumab+tucatinib × HER2 all showed null interactions despite adequate prevalences. The only treatment with a real PFS signal is regorafenib (+0.94 months adjusted, p<1e-300). Two priors went the wrong way: older age was associated with longer PFS, and NLR was not negative prognostic.
